{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_jemhadar_ver01/data/sn85042243/00383346162/1937111601/0686.xml":{"full_text":"Indications\n(the coming\ns\nt*\nr\u00ab\nf-M\n(Oi\nin\n\u2022\u00ab9\nfn\nIf*\nw\nIf.\np*\nvt\n13\nju\n|hi\nIPs\n[tie\n|.ba\ntoi\ncU\nra\nmovie\nIn\nan\nThe Bismarck Tribune\nAn Independent Newspaper\ni THE STATE'S OLDEST NEWSPAPER\n(Established 1873)\nState, City and County Official Newspaper\nPublished daily except Sunday by The Bismarck Tribune Company, Bls\ntttarck, N. D., and entered at the po6tofflce at Bismarck as second class mail\nnutter.\nMrs. Stella I. Mann\nPresident and Treasurer\nArchie O. Johnson Kenneth W. Simons\nVie* Fro. and Gen'l. Manager Secretary and Editor\nSubscription Rates Payable in Advance\nDally by carrier, per year $7.30\nDaily by mall per year (in Bismarck) 7.30\nDally by mail per year (in state outside of Bismarck) 6.00\nDaily by mail outside of North Dakota 6.00\nWeekly by mail In state, per year 1.00\nWeekly by mail outside of North Dakota, per year 1.50\nWeekly by mall in Canada, per year 2.00\nMember of Audit Bureau of Circulation\nMember of the Associated Press\nThe Associated tress li exclusively entitled to the us* for republica\ntion of the row* dispatches credited to It or not otherwlee credited In this\nnewspaper and also the local n*ws of spontaneoua origin published herein.\nA11 right* of republication of all other matter herein are alio reserved.\nThe Business Outlook\nThere is no question that business, uncertain as to the\ni'uture, would be improved by a sounder tax system and a more\n(definite outlook.\nnow are that it is quite likely to set them at\nsession of congress, whether or not the farmer gets\nnew and\nstreamlined law or the wage-hour bill is enacted.\nAt the same time, there is no disposition among intelligent\nobservers to minimize the importance of other factors which\nhave entered into the recent business recession. In fact, it\nseems, that conditions only indirectly traceable to government\nhave played an important part in the industrial recession.\nAn important straw in the wind is an article in a recent\nissue of the Wall Street Journal, headlined \"Much of new steel\nbusiness palls for early delivery.\"\nThis asserts that steel consumers have been reducing their\ninventories in recent weeks and this policy will continue to be\nfactor until \"stocks in the hands of users are brought down\nto a point considered justified under existing conditions.\"\nIn other words, while the sale of steel is going ahead pro\nduction is reduced. Steel now being sold was made some time\nAgo,\nwhereas steel now being made is for immediate delivery.\nThis condition emphasizes the speculative character of\nbusiness and gives rise to inquiry as to why this should be the\ncase.\nIt all goes back, probably, to the strikes in the steel mills\nlast spring. It is a habit of business to swing farther to one\nside or the other than is justified by the facts. It is as subject\nto hysteria as less responsible forces.\nThus, when labor trouble brewed, the urge was to stock\nup. Besides,, things were booming and the tendency was to\nprotect as much as possible both against price rises and the\npossible inability of the steel makers to deliver orders on time.\nThat phase of the business cycle now has passed. Because\nproduction and sale exceeded consumption in volume six months\nago they now are below consumption. As. noon as stocks in the\nhands of users are reduced, production and use probably will\nbe returned to balance. This will benefit the business struc\nture as a whole.\nStsel offers an outstanding example of the trend, but the\nsame factors doubtless prevail, to greater or lesser degree, in\nother industries.\nWhile production charts show peaks and valleys, consump\ntion has been both steady and at an increasingly high level, as\ndemonstrated by an article in a recent issue of the Magazine of\n.Wall Street, another publication.\nUnder the heading \"Retail Trade Confounds Pessimists,\"\nthis spokesman for business asserts that the strong posi\ntion of retail trade constitutes a refutation of statements made\n5\u00bby those whom it labels \"panicmongers.\"\nAsserting that retail trade has shown a steady increase\nevery month since the tide turned in August, 1933, it denies\n{that undue importance should be attached to the declining rate\nof this increase. This September, for example, was only 4.6\nper cent above September a year ago, but 1937 saw no release\nof soldier's bonus money such as injected life into all business\nIn the summer and fall of 1936.\nA quotation from this article clarifies the situation as fol\nlows:\n\"When things were booming last winter the heavy-goods man\ncomplained that retailers were not keeping up with the procession.\nThey were, but not ahead of the steadily rising demand of consumers.\nNow that production has been forced to pause to await absorption of\nthat speculative overproduction, heavy-goods men and Index reader*\nthink that all business Is in a similar recession.\n\"Of court* production is off. Of course car loadings are lower.\nIt is to be expected that lead, copper, scrap, cotton and other baste\ncommodity prices are lower than the Increased prices set hopefully\nduring last winter's boom when 10 and 16 per cent Jumps were com\nmonplaoe. But retail prices, because they did not go up correspond\ningly, have not receded. The Falrchlld retail price index waa 87.3\nat the beginning of 1935 rose to 88.0 during that year to 90.8 by the\nend of 1936 now stands at 96, and has held there since July.\n\"Obviously Industrial payrolls, one of the four factors contrib\nuting to retail sales, are responsible for much of the continued in\ncreases and may cause some sales recession this winter in reflection\nof heavy layoffs. The second factor, white-collar workers, aeem to\nhave received some salary Increases but broad data are lacking. As\na class they exert the most effect on retail sales in all but the food\ncategory. Their buying should continue unchanged unless the scare\ncampaign is kept up. The third factor, affecting medium to luxury\ngoods, is composed of dividend and interest recipients and business\nproprietors.\n\"The fourth factor affecting retail sales is farm income, pro\nviding the buying power of farmers, farm labor and moat business\nand professional men in agricultural communities. There is no\nreason yet to reduce the previous estimate of 9 billions of farm\nincome the recent statements of Sears, Ward, Spiegel, Chicago\nMail Order and Penney show no evidence of any change in the\nsteady trend of rural buying. The Department of Commerce reports\nthe highest such sales of any September since 1939.\"\nTo have these conservative publications take such a mod\nerate view of prevailing conditions is encouraging. Such ex\npressions as \"panicmongers\" and \"scare campaign\" are their\nown\u2014and rather unusual in such publications.\nBut, more than anything else, they tend to give the stock\nmarket its proper place in the American business scheme. They\ndo the business world a favor by analyzing the current situation\nwithout bittefness or bias.\nThe tax system should be further revised, if for no other\nreason because it has failed to produce the revenue expected.\nAnother cogent fact is that business needs stability, such as\ncan be achieved only by\na\nbalanced budget and the assurance\nJthat the era of experimentation is over.\nBusiness can stand higher taxes. If the budget is to be\nbalanced it will have to do so. The thing it cannot stand is con\ntinued instability, brought about by uncertainly as to what con*\nCress may do.\nJohnny Weissmuller, Tarsan Jungle yeller, speaks for first time in new\nrole. When the fundamentalists bear of this, he may also be cast\na new evolution case.\nIn Variety claims\n'language?\n\u2022nek tea\nU Rolls Seven on Nov. Sited.\" Who said\nBehind\nWashington\nThis is the first of six stories by Rod\nney Dutcher on the program and\nprobabilities ahead of the special\nsession of Congress.\nBy RODNEY DUTCHER\n(Tribune Washington Correspondent)\nWashington, Nov. 16.\u2014The toughest\nCongress with which President Roose\nvelt has yet had to deal now reassem\nbles. This Is the same Congress which\nbalked the Roosevelt program last\nspring and summer. It was summon\ned Into a special session opening Nov.\nIS to enact the same program-minus\nthat court plan.\nPredictions as to what this Congress\nwill do and as to the extent to which\nit will co-operate with Roosevelt\nprobably are as dangerous as those\nmade last year after the huge Demo\ncratic election victory, when most of\nus thought F. D. R. could get ap\nproximately what he wanted from\nCapitol Hill.\nPlenty of stormy weather may be\nsafely forecast, but more legislative re\nsults than were had from the last\nCongress seem fairly certain.\nThe issue of centralization of power,\nboth as to expanded federal control\nand increased presidential powers, will\nbe almost constantly in the fore\nground.\nIn the background will be gen\neral concern with the primaries and\nelections of 1938, the plottings of con\nservatives and liberals thinking in\ntfrms of 1940 and efforts of southern\nand other Democrats to see that\nRoosevelt doesn't control the next\nDemocratic national convention.\nEither the domestic business situa\ntion or the international situation may\nlead to developments not now antici\npated.\nThe Same Old List\nThe problems before Congress are\nall familiar. The proposed wage-hour\nlegislation has as its aim the same\nchief objective announced more than\nfour years ago for NRA.\nSurplus crop control, tried first in\n1933, is second on the list.\nThe regional development proposal\ncalls for an extension of the TV A idea\nthrough the nation.\nGovernment reorganization, Roose\nvelt's fourth special session item, has\nbeen talked of and vainly stabbed at\nfor 35 years.\nAnti-monopoly legislation, if any,\nwill be a new attempt to meet an an\ncient issue.\nThey're all old, but they're also all\nhotly controversial.\nTew will be surprised if no im\nportant legislation is passed before\nChristmas. The special session and\nthe regular session beginning in Jan\nuary almost immediately afterward\nmay be considered as a whole.\nDiverse and Two-edged\nThe factors to be weighed in specu\nlating as to the extent Roosevelt will\nget what he asks are diverse and\noften two-edged.\nAbsence of the court plan, which\ngummed everything up in the first ses\nsion, is one. The coalition which\nfought Roosevelt on the court will not\nget together again\u2014at least not with\nout conspicuous absentees. On the\nother hand, that fight left acars.\nThe President called the special ses\nsion with an obvious burst of aelf\nconfidence, baaed on his reception\nduring his western tour and conviction\nthat the people were still strong for\nhim. Yet the point is made that en\nthusiasm for Roosevelt doesn't mean\neffective popular aupport on specific\nissues and there seems no enthusiaatic\nmass furore over any item on his\ncurrent program.\nCongress meets at what may be\neither side of the half-way point in a\nbusiness slump and theoretically this\nshould permit the President more\nscope in solving economic problems.\nBut there will also be plenty of at\ntack and the New Deal's enemies in\nCongress will blame its policies for a\n\"new depression.\"\nBusiness Lobbies Busy\nSome of the most effective Demo\ncratic opponents of the oourt plan\noften will be with the President In\nthe next few months, and others will\ndisplay a passion for regularity.\nSenator Wheeler of Montana, has\nsaid he expects to support Roosevelt\non labor, farm and other \"progressive\"\nissues.\nO'Mahoney of Wyoming will demon\nstrate his friendship.\nConnally of Texas, and other anti\ncourt man, will be reasonably regular.\nBut auch conservative Democrats as\nCopeland of New York, Byrd and\nOlass of Virginia, Bailey of North\nCarolina, Tydings of Maryland, Burke\nof Nebraska, Smith of South Carolina,\nGeorge of Georgia and Van Nuya of\nIndiana, aa well as a number of south'\nera committee chairmen, will often be\nfound with the opposition.\nAnd on top of that you probably\nwill find business interests lobbying\nmore intensively than ever for certain\nmodifications of previous New Deal\nlegislation, aa well aa against the cur\nrent administration agenda.\n(Copyright, 1937, NBA Service, Inc.)\nBulletins\n2 KILLED IN CRASH\nFredericksburg, Va^-Two\nrine officers stationed at\ntico were killed instantly In the\ncrash of a plane near here Tuee\nday. The two killed were Staff\nSergeant Herman L. Williams, ef\nGreenville, 8. C, who waa pilot\ning the plane, and Sergeant (Nee\n8. Bower, of Corning, Ark.\nRECOVER BODY\nCalumet. Mich.\u2014The body of Waltei\nLaurin, 41, fireman of Hancock, was\nremoved from debria left by a freight\ntrain wreck which also claimed the\nlife of Joseph Schneiderhahn, 56, the\nengineer.\nKILLED IN EXPLOSION\nChicago.\u2014Two men were killed\nand ten injured when a hot water\nheater exploded In a sanitary\nbuilding at the Carnegie-Illinois\nSteel company's South Chicago\nTABER HEADS GRANGE\nHarrisburg, Pa., Nov. 16.\u2014UPj\u2014Louli\nTaber of Columbus, Ohio, waa re\nelected master of the National Grangt\nMonday for Ma eighth term.\nTHE BISMARCK TRIBUNE,\nBISMARCK STREETS\nWILL BE SET ASIDE\nFDR SLED COASTING\nStop Signs Will Be Set Up to\nWarn Motorists of Re\nserved Areas\nBismarck's city fathera had\nthought for Capital City youngsters\nMonday night.\nTaking heed of the coming of win'\nter and snow they decided to set\naside certain streets on which boy\nand girls may coast without too mush\nfear of oncoming cars. The streets\nwill be marked with stop signs, the\ncommission decided.\n\"The kids will coast on these streets\nwhether we mark them or not,\" as\nserted Commissioner H. T. Perry, \"and\nwe might as well make it as safe for\nthem as possible.\"\nParenta Warned\nIt was explained that while chil\ndren cannot be effectively prevented\nfrom coasting on other streets mark'\ninga few streets where children from\nthroughout entire nelghborhods con\ngregate will relieve a good share of\ndanger. Parents were urged to warn\ntheir children to keep to the deslg\nnated streets while coasting and to\nuse caution even then.\nStreets to be marked are Twelfth\nSt. between Avenue and Roaser\nAve. Mandan St. north of Ave.\nSouth Tenth St. from Bowen to In\ndiana avenues, and Thayer Ave. be\ntween Hannafln and West Park St.\nDecision to use a WPA labor grant\nto install 380 feet of sewer pipe on\nWashington St. between Avenues\nand C, and 200 feet of three-incn\nwater main at the same place and to\nlaw 175 feet of sewer on First St.\nbetween Avenues and E, was arrived\nat.\nMain Flans Approved\nPlans and specifications for a water\nmain on Sweet St. were approved and\nthe city auditor waa Instructed to\nadvertise for bids for its construe\ntion.\nThe commission also decided that\nwhere a second survey by the city\nengineer for a sidewalk grade Is re\nquired the cost of the second wi'.l\nbe charged to the owner and assessed\nagainst the property. It was ex\nplained that this was done because\noften the city engineer is called upon\nto make the survey when only private\nwalks are laid and later must repeat\nthe survey before the public walk\ncan be laid.\nCommissioner E. B. Klein was not\npresent.\nXJUBSjlXJEWS\nHOTEL REGISTRATIONS\nGrand Pacific Hotel\nH. J. Reynolds and family, Harvey\nS. P. Sullivan, Park River Mr. and\nMrs. A. C. Kline, Detroit Lakes Mr.\nand Mrs. C. M. Hanson, Crosby Mr.\nand Mrs. C. W. Wise, Newport, Ark.\nH. Z. Anderson, R. W. Brownie*.\nFarsro W. S. Sutton, Hunter James\nSpiekermeler, Sheldon D. A. Wal\nstrom, Wahpeton Otto Prlta, Binford\nW. M. Lunde, Cooperstown Thomai\nDailey, Hanaford\nw.\nA. Larson, Dick\u00ad\ninson F. C. Weller, Grand Forks\nMargaret O. Brltton.Turtle Lake and\nThomas C. Barker, Linton.\nBirths\nDaughter, Mr. and Mra. Fred Kiat,\nMandan. at 4:40 a. m. Tuesday, Bis\nmarck hospital.\nDaurhter, Mr. and Mrs. Harold Nord,\n413 We\u00bbt Thayer, at 8:53 a. m. Tues\nday, Bismarck.\nHearing on the complaint of Walter\nJ. Moris, Pembina, who contends the\ntransmission line of the Interstate\nPower Co., Dubuque, la., causes inter\nference with telephone service, has\nbeen set for Dee. 3 at Neche by the\nNorth Dakota board of railroad com\nmissioners.\nCompetitive examinations will be\ngiven applicants for federal govern\nment Jobs shortly, Paul Halloran, sec\nxetary of the U. S civil service board\nof examiners, announces. The gov\nernment is seeking draftsmen, ento-\nCrete.\nI Nocturnal Bird\nHORIZONTAL\n1 Pictured bird.\n4 It has a large\n26 Song for on*\nvoice.\n27 Insurgent.\n29 Corded cloth.\n30 South Caro\nlina.\n32 Cut with a\naaw.\n34 Southeast.\nanon nrnrann\nI It has a abort\nbill.\n13 Falsehoods.\nIS Smell.\n17 In this place.\n18 Making into\na drama.\n21 Brooch*\n32 To prepare\nfor publi\ncation.\n23 Branching\nfigures.\n24 Native of\nTUESDAY, iNUVifJMBER 16,1937\nmologlsts, scientific aides and stew\nards. Further details may be Obtained\nfrom Halloran in the federal building.\nNorth Dakota will be represented\nst the fourth national congress of the\nAmerican League Against War and\nFascism to be held at Pittsburgh, Pa.,\nNov. 36. Herbert J. Roberts. Bismarck,\nsaid Monday. Delegates were to be\nstiected at a mass open forum.\nCharles K. Otto, Valley City post\nmaster who underwent an operation to\nrelieve an intestinal condition in a\nlocal hospital several days ago is\n\"coming along very well,\" his physic\nian said Monday.\nUncle Sam won't permit people to\nbundle up N. D. auto license applica\ntions hereafter and obtain a lower\npostal rate. Walter Ton. postal in\nspector, announces all letters contain\ning license applications must bear\npostage at a rate of 3 cents per appli\ncation.\nE. W. Norcross, deputy state seed\ncommissioner who Judged the recent\nstate corn show In Bismarck, has been\nnamed one of the five judges at the\nInternational Grain and Hay show in\nChicago, Nov. 27 to Dec. 4. Norcross\nis the first North Dakotan ever chosen\nfor this honored task.\nMandan Masons will advance and\nelect new officers at the annual meet\ning of blue lodge at 7:30 p. m. (MST)\nTuesday. W. P. Balrd is retiring mas\nter.\nM. D. Hollis, state sanitary engi\nneer, halted work on the new Grand\nForks water supply when he discov\nered two sewer outlets upstream from\nthe site of the new plant. Remedial\nsteps are under consideration.\nNorthwest Airlines has placed its\nnew Zephyrs in operation between\nChicago and Seattle but does not have\nthe modern transport stop in Bis\nmack. Four additional ships have\nbeen ordered by the company.\nJ. K. Wallace, senior marketing\nspecialist for the U. S. department of\nagriculture, conducted a demonstra\nion Tuesday on the H. D. Henke farm\nat Hannover.\nE. J. Kapsner was elected president\nof the newly organized Mandan chap\nter of the St. Vincent de Paul society,\ncharitable association. Other officers\nare W. J. Lantz, vice president Dr. A.\nC. Braxmeier, secretary J. M. Gauer,\ntreasurer Rev. Hlldebrand Eickoff,\nspiritual director.\nColliding with a truck en route to\nhis home from Bismarck Saturday\nnight, Dan Preszler suffered a knee\ninjury compelling hospitalization at\nJamestown. The Medina merchant\nreported resting easily.\nHenry Jordan, 33, who faces federal\nmanslaughter charges In connection\nwith the death Oct. 9 of Mary Jane\nWhite, Fort Yates Indian girl, will\ngiven a preliminary hearing be\nfore U. 8. Commissioner J. H. Noakes\nMandan Wednesday at 3 p. m\u201e\n(MST).\nState Engineer E. J. Thomas and\nFloyd Jennings, executive director of\nthe North Dakota planning board,\nill leave Tuesday for Hazen where\nthey will speak on conservation and\nirrigation at a meeting of the Hazen\nCivic and Commerce association.\nLuella Pahl, young daughter of Mr.\nard Mrs. Hans Pahl of Elgin, N. D.,\nwho broke her arm when throwing\nball proved too much of a strain on\nhitherto undetected bone tumor, is\nback at home now apparently well on\nher way to recovery.\nMore Than 60 to Be\nat Dealers Meeting\nRegional and district representa\ntives of the Chrysler and Plymouth\nmotor car companies will lead a meet\ning of more than 60 automobile deal\ners of Bismarck and vicinity in the\nPrince hotel tonight sponsored by Cor\nwin-Churchill Motors.\nSound slide films and technical dia\ngrams will be shown to acquaint deal\ners with the new 1938 models and the\nowners-service policy will be discussed\nand explained.\nAnswer to Previous Fuszle\nI\niramran uoiriid\nramra nnfunn EffiH\nn^nnnnflnl|||i|\narcannH\narar-iHia mnH mmmraH\nraaan annna naac\nratio mannHQH oran\nIFIAIRI IE IE i. I\nfnraraa ram nu nann\nnranrn waunra\n39 To make lace. 57 Councils of 9 Sound of\n37 Lawful. elders. surprise.\n39To soak flax. MIt eats small lORetained.\n11 Great lak'e.\n12 Lairs.\n14 Strikes.\n16 Srtialler.\n19 Kettledrum.\n20 Serranoid\nfish.\n24 Price.\n25 More modern.\n28 Envoy.\n[8] 31 To find fault.\n33 Marking the\ndate.\n36 Afternoon\nmeals.\n33 Small lance.\n40 Greater\ncalorie.\n42 Ogles.\n43 Caterpillar\nhair.\n44 Cetacean.\n47 Portuguese\ncoins.\n48 Wings.\n49 To fail to hit\n51 Palmyra.\n52 To bring\nlegal suit.\n55 Within.\n58 Street.\nhhfjb\n\u2022unmra DHQ nranni\nmwsHia\n41 Assessment and\namounts. other living\n43 Algerian cav- -J things.\nairy corps. 0 Muscid flies.\n45 Prong. VERTICAL\n46 Metric unit Ancient,\nof weight. 2 Wireman.\nSO Judicial 3 Commander,\ndecrees/ STo dine.\n93 Prophet. 6 Dry.\n94 Note in acale. 7 Naps.\n36 Inlet Touches.\nEnglish and Speaking1\nClasses Are Plannec\nFirst of a series of weekly classes\nin practical English and public speak'\ning will be held In the dining room of\nthe Grand Pacific hotel at 7:30 p. m.,\nWednesday, Roy Holland, instructor,\nannounced Tuesday.\nSponsored by the Bismarck Junior\nAssociation of Commerce, the classes\nare open to others as well as to mem\nbers of the junior association. Mem\nbers will study correct pronunciation\ntone of voice, private conversation\nsocial and business conversation and\npublic speaking, and will be given op\nporunity to prepare and deliver talks.\nTexts which will be used are \"How\nto Talk,\" by John Clapp and Edwin\nKane, and \"How to Win Friends and\nInfluence People,\" by Dale Carnegie,\nThe first meeting will be dismissed\nearly enough to permit members to\nattend the concert at the city audi\ntorium Wednesday night, Holand said\nArrest May Clear\nUp Fargo Thefts\nFargo, N. D., Nov. 16.\u2014W\u2014Several\nFargo house burglaries were believed\nsolved Tuesday after a jewelry store\nclerk recognized articles which were\noffered for sale as old gold as having\nbeen stolen from his aunt's home.\nPolice are holding Kenneth Barnes,\n34. Fargo, who has admitted prowling\nseveral homes In which clothing, Jew\nelry, silverware and other articles were\ntaken.\nE. W. Ericson, the clerk, recognized a\nring and two gold chains which Barnes\nattempted to sell. When he questioned\nBarnes, the alleged thief fled. Eric\nson and several other men captured\nhim after a chase of several blocks\nPolice recovered two automobile loads\nof loot at Barnes' home.\nTalbott Doesn't Want\nto Head National Union\nOklahoma City, Nov 16.\u2014W)\u2014Glenn\nJ. Talbott, 37, president of the North\nDakota Farmers Union, met talk of\nhis candidacy for president of the\nnational organization Tuesday wlch\nthe statement:\n\"I've been in the Farmers' Union\nall my life, but I've been a member\nof the official family only about a\nyear. A fellow has to be practical\npbout such things, and I don't believe\nit would do me or the union any good\nto be named president.\"\nApproximately 6,000 members from\n36 states are expected for the national\nconvention, opening Tuesday.\nTo Name Director of\nGNDA in New England\nSelection of a district director for\nthe Greater North Dakota association\nwill be made at a meeting ataged\nby New England businessmen tonight.\nO. Ryan, Fargo, secretary, will\noutline current activities of the or\nganization. The new director will suc\nceed M. J. Connolly, who moved to\nValley City.\n3 Youths Get Life\nfor Kidnaping Man\nLouisville, Ky., Nov. 16.\u2014(R)\u2014'Three\nyouths, Samuel Hornback, 30, Bernard\nKettler. 20, and Edward Metcalf, 19,\nfaced life imprisonment Tuesday for\nkidnaping Simeon Jacobs, attorney,\nand robbing him of $39.\nalan\nWau ILL\nCAST or CHARACTERS\nJILL WENTWORTH. kcnlu,\nattractive iikatntc.\njarrar, ken,\nrtaia*\ny\u00bbiav artist.\nBARRY WBNTWOBTH, Jlll'a\nStepbrother.\nJACK WBNTWOBTH, Jlll'a\nbrother.\nSYLVIA SUTTON, ell heticaa.\nYtstcrSayi Ailitk HoIm acta\nher cap (or Alaa. after kli fcrealc\nwith Jill, aaS arrive*\niuuiiumI\neae day at fcta atatlo-\nCHAPTER XII\nMl HOPE I'm not Intruding. Per\nhaps you are busy,\" Ardath\nbegan, humbly enough.\nShe had long ago realized that\nhumility is a becoming role for a\nwoman dealing with a proud and\nspirited man.\n\"I remembered the lovely pic\ntures, and I wanted to aea them\nin a nicer place.\"\n\"No,\" Alan heard himself say\ning, to his own amazement, in a\ncourteous tone that held none of\nhis previous irritation. \"I waa\npainting, but It is nothing that\ncannot wait.\"\n\"Oh, please! I'd love to see a\npicture in the making. Couldn't\nI?\"\nAlan was amazed at her inter\nest. He had not expected artistic\nenthusiasm from this girl. He\nhad not expected anything. He\nhad scarcely been aware of her\nthose other times.\nA tempestuous nature lurked\nbehind the calm, almost expres\nsionless face, he felt sure. She\nmight be none too sharp intellec\ntually, but she Was emotionally,\nAlan realized.\nUE would like to put her on\ncanvas. Paint her as a woman\nwho was emotionally asleep, with\na slow, sluggish smile on her wide,\nmobile mouth. A smile that just\ntouched her sleepy eyes. And\nthen paint her again as a woman\nawakened, with a fierce, posses\nsive light in her eyes, her lips\ncurved for a caress.\nAlan had forgotten his prejudice\nagainst having a woman, or any\nstranger, invade his private sanc\ntum, and had led the way back to\nthe studio. He raised the shade\nhigh in the windowed recess, so\nthat the rich tints of his picture\nmight be revealed to his visitor.\nHe looked at his portrait the\nregal head of a young Russian\naristocrat, as he remembered her.\n\"I like it,\" Ardath said.\nAlan warmed to the simple\nstatement. She was ignorant, he\nknew. Very ignorant about cul\ntural things. But she made no\npretense of knowledge, for which\nbe admired her.\n\"I don't suppose,\" Ardath spoke\nabruptly, \"that you would care to\npaint me?\"\nHe did want to paint her. But\nYour Personal Health\nBy William Brady, M. D.\n\u201e.,ls Mi,:,1,1ssrujsswrfWfM\nIn care of The Tribune. All queriea muit ba accompanied by a atampafl.\naelf-addrawtd envelope.\nINBREEDING AND CROSSBREEDING\nMarriage of near-of-kin is forbidden by nearly all peoples, civilized or\nuncivilized. Only in ancient Egypt and Peru was marriage of brother and\nsister sanctioned in the royal families, because of a belief that the royal\nfamily were a superior race and outside of it there were no suitable mates\nto be found.\nIn animal husbandry some such consideration, that Is, a desire to per\npetuate superior qualities of selected stock, favors inbreeding, that is, the\nmating of closely related Individuals. But the closest possible inbreeding\nis the natural way of reproduction among many/plants this Is known aa\nself-pollination, in which the egg cells of the plant are fertilized by pollen\ncells produced by the same Individual. Self-fertilization or hermaphroditic\nreproduction occurs in some animal parasites and fishes.\nCommon peas, wheat, oats and most other cereals are naturally self\nfertilizing, and most plants thrive best that way. Maize or Indian corn,\nhowever, seems to decline in size and vigor if left to self-pollination In\ndefinitely but racial vigor and size may be fully restored by a cross breed\ning\u2014fertilization of corn by pollen from a plant (obtained by self-fertiliza\ntion) of distant kin.\nAnimal experiments indicate that close inbreeding has no ill effects in\nthe earlier generations but if continued through a long line eventually bringa\ndegeneration. A steady decline both in fertility and in alze and vigor or\nvitality finally terminates the experiment. In animal economy it is gen\nerally recognized as essential to add new blood to the strain or family at\nnot too great intervals to prevent this decline in size, vigor and reprodue\ntivc capacity.\nThere is no ground for the notion that monstrosities or defective chil\ndren result from the mating of closely related individuals. Of course if\nthere Is any inherent trait in the family, the marriage of first cousins, for\nexample, would increase by 100 per cent the chance of transmitting the\ntrait to off-spring.\nBecause of the universal prohibition of close inter-marriage it is dif\nficult to learn what would be the ultimate effect of close inbreeding for\nmany generations of man\u2014beginning with normal individuals. Something\nof the sort occurred on Pitcairn Island, where 10 sailors, deserters from the\nBounty, established themselves, with six native men and 12 native women.\nAfter 20 years the sole survivors of this party, on an island one mile wide,\ntwo miles long, were one Englishman and eight or nine women and their\nchildren. After 67 years the population of the island had increased to 200\u2014\nand it began to be crowded. Then the British government granted their\npetition and removed them to Norfolk Island where they might have more\nroom. Fifty years later the population of Norfolk island was 870, mostly\ndescendants of the Pitcairn Islanders. 8ome of them later voluntarily re\nturned to Pitcairn. In all perhaps a thousand persons, out of a cross\nbetween English men and Tahitian women and close inbreeding among their\nchildren. So far as the experiment went the results were excellent biologically\nand sociologically.\n(Copyright, 1937, John F. Dille Co.)\nBarnesville Crash\nVictim Near Death\nWatertown, S. D., Nov. 16.\u2014(ffV\u2014A\nMinnesota camera salesman, identi\nfied by letters found in his wrecked\ncar as S. E. Rice, Barnesville, was\nnear death in fNiospital following a\ntruck-automobile accident a mile east\nof here Tuesday morning. His car\nswerved at right angles on the toe\ncoated highway and crashed into a\ntruck loaded with three and a ha.f\ntons of cement.\nOne Firm Capitulates\nin Sioux Falls Strike\nSioux Falls, 8. D\u201e Nov. 16.\u2014(J?)\u2014The\nfirst break in the strike of Sioux Falls\ntruckers came Tuesday aa union of\nficials reported one firm had capitu\nlated and that two others had entered\ninto contracts with their employes\nwho were not Involved in the walk\nout.\nNAMED AS ACCOMPLICE\nFargo, N. D., Nov. 16.\u2014(/P)\u2014Named\nby Kenneth Bares, Fargo, aa his com\njanion In a series of Fargo house burg\nlaries recently, Leo Madson, 38, Fargo,\nwas arrested by police Tuesday.\nhe was unprepared for her direct\nquestion. Paradoxically, he didnt\nwant to paint her. He had a\nfeeling that perhaps contact with\nthis sultry young person might\nnot be especially good for him. At\nleast not especially rewarding ar\ntistically.\nTT waa all very well to visualize\nher on two canvases. But\nting her there especially\nmood his imagination had evoked,\nwith her full lips parted to reveal\ngleaming teeth\u2014might bo more\ndifficult. Rather than be an in\nspiration, she might play havoc\nwith it\n\"I don't know,\" Alan tempo\nrized. \"Have you ever posed for\npictures?\"\n\"I'm a model for clothes,\" Ar\ndath replied. \"I pose every day\nfor somebody. I shouldn't think\nit would be so very different.\"\n\"Very different,\" Alan said.\n\"Posing for clothes doesn't require\nany mental effort. But when an\nartist demands a mood\u2014\"\n\"What kind of mood?\" Ardath\nquestioned, her eyes on his.\nAlan colored. Never mind that.\nIf this girl thought she could\nforce him into confidences, ahe\nwas mistaken. His thoughts were\nhis own. There had never been\na woman yet he would care to\nshare them with.\nYes, there had been one. A\nbeautiful clear-eyed girl, whose\nclear eyes had masked deceit. The\nmost dreadful of all deceits. A\nconspiracy to topple his pride and\nprofessional integrity. A conspir\nacy to make a soft fool of him.\nThe thought of Jill, bringing\nwith it again the pain of broken\nromance and disillusionment,\nmade him feel more tolerant of\nthis girl with her purposes so hon\n:tly exposed. Yes, she would\nprobably prove an apt model.\nHe didn't like her. He dis\ntrusted her. But he might paint\nher.\n\"I think,\" drawled Ardath,\nwho had watched indecision play\ning over his face, and read It\nwisely, \"that I'll leave my addreaa\nand telephone number. After all,\nyou might need a model, aome\nday. Who knows?\"\nA FTER she had gone he looked\nat the small card. Ardath\nHolm. The name seemed to suit.\nThe address, he told himself,\nmeant nothing to him.\nIt was Just aa well to tear it up,\nthis small card that was a tan\ngible temptation of aome kind.\nBut instead, Alan crossed to a\ndesk and dropped tbe card into a\ndrawer which held some receipts\nand more unpaid bills.\nThe next day Alan, aaw Jill's I\"* Invitation,\npicture, as he carelaasly turned (11a Be\nMinoters Proud\nof 1909 Vehicle\nD. D. Whaley's touring car\n(Model Ford), handsome and\nshiny in Its heyday 28 years ago,\nis still rattling around Minot\nstreets\u2014and the pride of the\nWhaley home.\nThe ancient vehicle has no\npeers in the North Dakota motor\nvehicle department even among\nexpensive makes with modern\ngadgwta and sweeping streamlines.\nIt is the oldest car registered and\nholds a perfect record alnoe the\nowner purchased his first license\nplatea in 1910. It was manufactur\ned in 1909.\nHalt Spending in\nCass Pending Suit\nFargo, N. D., NOT. 16.\u2014(J) Spend\nlng of the current tax levy In Caw\ncounty has been halted pending an ac\nbefore the supreme court In which\nan attempt is being made to prevent\nthe state from levying 6.1 mills.\nIf an elephant, proportionately to\naiae, ate as much food as a mouse,\nwould consume 10 tons of fodder\ndaily.\nBY\nRAYMOND\nMARY\nCopyright NBA Sanies, lit\nthe pages of a newspaper.\nJill, he read grimly, waa having\na ball. The date was some time\naway, but the event waa heralded\nas one of major importance in the\nwinter calendar.\nTha brilliant ball was one Mrs.\nWentworth had had in mind a\nlong while. She wanted it to\neclipae any social affair Jill had\nit put-lever been given and to rank with\nin the the elaborate parties of the sea\nson.\nIt would be, Jill thought, with a\nnew cynicism, exactly like a bold\nlabel: \"Look what the debutantes\nof this season have to offer. And\nthen look at what marriage with\nthe daughter of John Wentworth\noffers. Not to be ignored even If\nher debut is two seaaona cold.\"\n|-|bk mother was desperately\neager for her to marry. Well,\nin this respect she waa not ao very\ndifferent from moat of the other\nmothers, Jill thought. All of them\nwere anxloua to weep at daugh\nters' weddings, and give the bride\ngroom a grateful peck on the\ncheek for taking than away.\nWell, at least, die would com\npromiae regarding the ball, end\nbe paraded once more.\nAnd then came an electric,\ndaring thought. She would aend\nan invitation to Alan. Patty would\nlearn his address. From Ardath\nHolm, if necessary.\nJill felt almost lighthearted as\nshe played with the happy idea,\nwhich waa entirely within the\nrealm of possibilities.\n'I can't understand your sud\nden enthusiasm for the party,*\nMrs. Wentworth said, fixing Jill\nwith a speculative eye. \"Is there\nsome special reason?\"\n\"Nothing special!\" Jill's voice\nsang, as she prevaricated bravely.\nShe added, a little anxiously,\n\"Sometimes I think maybe we\nshouldn't have auch a large parly,\nmother. Haven't you noticed\nfather has been looking worried\nlately?\"\n\"Nonsense.\" Mra. Wentworth'a\nvoice was sharp. \"What could he\npossibly have to worry about?\nMost men look worried. It's\nway they have of impressing their\nwives with their\nfanpnrtyi\u00ab+.\nEvery husband thinks of hhwfif\nas an Atlas going around with\nthe world on his shoulders. You\nnever see any of them cutting out\nparties they want to give because\nof the expense.\"\nJust tbe same, Jill resolved, IH\nsound father out. All her ro\nmancing of the moment before\nseemed childish and absurd now.\nIf father didnt want the parly,\nthey wouldn't have one.\nIf he did, she would send\nV\nAla\"","height":"27348","width":"20952"}}
